snippet.textDisplay: Marvi is widely known in Sindh and celebrated for her courage. Her legendary status is largely due to one man - Shah Latif, who sang her in his poetry in classical Sindhi. Latif's account of Marvi is what is taken to be a literal one, whether factual or otherwise. Some even doubt the existence of a real Marvi, but thanks to Latif she has become a legend, a symbol of resistence in the face of endless agony, greed of wealth and kindly comforts, as she chose to return back to her poor folk and not give in to all the pressures of her abductor.

snippet.textDisplay:
Background of the song:

Basically a girl, Marvi, from Thar, was captured by local emperor,  who wants to marry Marvi. But Marvi loved someone else. After so many refusals to emperor,  he kidnapped her and locked her in his fort. He gave her threats, many offers, wealth to accept his proposal but she refused. After years in prison, finally emperor release her. Upon arrival in her tribe, she passed a Purity test (of being not rapped), and locals sung this song in honor of her.
